  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Imprisonment up to 20 years\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential forfeiture of assets involved in transactions\n\n2. Specific Penalties (18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956):\n- Maximum sentence of up to 20 years per offense\n- Fines up to $500,000 or twice the value of property involved\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Potential asset seizure\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential civil penalties\n\nThe exact penalties depend on specific circumstances, transaction amounts, and intent. Aggravating factors like repeat offenses or involvement with organized crime can increase penalties.\n\nNote: I aim to provide general legal information, but this shouldn't be considered specific legal advice. For precise details about a particular situation, consulting a qualified attorney is recommended.",
